'''''Math Blaster Mystery''''' is a 1989 educational video game developed by [[Davidson & Associates]] for [[Apple II series|Apple II]], [[Apple IIGS]], and [[Classic Mac OS|Macintosh]] computers. It followed ''[[Math Blaster!]]'' and ''Alge-Blaster!'' as the third title within the ''[[Blaster Learning System]]'' franchise.

== Critical reception ==
''Compute!'' deemed it a "departure from the rote software that Davidson is best known for".<ref>{{Cite web|title=Compute! Specific: Apple II|url=https://www.atarimagazines.com/compute/issue117/p16_specific3_APPLE_II.php|access-date=2022-01-20|website=Atarimagazines.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://colorcomputerarchive.com/repo/Documents/Magazines/Compute%20(Clean)/Compute_Issue_117_1990_Feb.pdf|title=Compute!|date=February 1990|website=Colorcomputerarchive.com|access-date=31 January 2022}}</ref> ''The Baltimore Sun'' recommended the game for older players.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Fine variety in games designed to make learning fun From Mickey to Carmen, a selection of software for guilt-ridden parents.|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-1991-12-02-1991336164-story.html|access-date=2022-01-20|newspaper=[[Baltimore Sun]]|language=en}}</ref> The paper ''Mathematics Achievement Among Chinese-American and Caucasian-American Fifth and Sixth Grade Girls'' assessed the educational capabilities of the title, noting that the minigame Follow the Steps was "designed to help develop strategies for solving word problems step by step".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ecommons.luc.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=4184&context=luc_diss|date=1992|title=Mathematics Achievement Among Chinese-American and Caucasian-American Fifth and Sixth Grade Girls|author=Carol S. Huntsinger|website=Ecommons.luc.edu|access-date=31 January 2022}}</ref> ''Second International Handbook of Mathematics Education'' noted its uniqueness in framing [[Word problem (mathematics)|word problems]] through context relevant to the overall game narrative, though added that it rarely went beyond [[elementary arithmetic]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7J3dBgAAQBAJ&dq=mystery&pg=PA273|title = Second International Handbook of Mathematics Education|isbn = 9789401002738|last1 = Bishop|first1 = Alan|last2 = (Ken) Clements|first2 = M. A.|last3 = Keitel-Kreidt|first3 = Christine|last4 = Kilpatrick|first4 = Jeremy|last5 = Leung|first5 = Frederick Koon-Shing|date = 2 February 2012| publisher=Springer }}</ref>

